## Context
The NCC epic (0012) was killed because "Paris didn't matter" oversold
the data. But the periodization question is real and the existing
analysis has genuine signal. A proper paper needs:

1. Continuous divergence (MMD, energy distance, or sliced Wasserstein)
   on embeddings — no clustering, no arbitrary k
2. TF-IDF divergence as independent lexical signal (exposes language
   boundaries that embeddings hide)
3. Citation graph dynamics (2-3 methods from: community rewiring,
   authority displacement, cross-tradition citation, preferential
   attachment breakdown, bibliographic coupling age shift)
4. External validation on 2-3 known-break corpora from OpenAlex
   (COVID-19 in public health, AlexNet in AI/ML, 2008 financial crisis)
5. Honest framing: Copenhagen was the dominant founding shift,
   mid-2010s saw real redistribution, core shows no break

## Not yet decomposed
This is a future epic. Decompose when it becomes the next priority.

## Exit criteria
Paper submitted to a bibliometrics venue (QSS, Scientometrics, or
similar). Validated on external cases. Honest about what the data shows.
